WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
Weddings by Christine Lindopt, read by Nicolette McKenzie.

00:12.000 --> 00:16.000
Chapter 1 A long time ago.

00:22.000 --> 00:25.000
Everybody loves a wedding.

00:25.000 --> 00:37.000
It is a happy day, a day for blue skies and flowers, for family and friends, for music and dance.

00:38.000 --> 00:51.000
Some weddings are very small with just five or six people, and other weddings cost thousands of dollars and have hundreds of people.

00:52.000 --> 01:05.000
But in every wedding, there are two very important people, the bride, the woman, and the groom, the man.

01:06.000 --> 01:12.000
For them, the wedding is when their new life begins.

01:13.000 --> 01:25.000
When was the first wedding? Nobody knows, of course. But there were weddings in Egypt thousands of years ago.

01:26.000 --> 01:30.000
In some ways, they were like weddings today.

01:31.000 --> 01:38.000
The Egyptian man and woman got engaged before they got married.

01:39.000 --> 01:48.000
The groom and his parents visited the bride and her family and gave them money.

01:49.000 --> 01:59.000
The groom gave a present to his bride too. Often, it was something made of gold.

02:00.000 --> 02:09.000
At the wedding, there was lots of food and people sang and danced.

02:10.000 --> 02:18.000
Long ago, in Rome, the father of the bride looked for a groom for her.

02:19.000 --> 02:32.000
But often, his daughter found her man first. Then, the fathers of the bride and the groom arranged things between them.

02:33.000 --> 02:45.000
The bride needed to be twelve years old or more and a groom thirteen or more before they could get married.

02:46.000 --> 02:57.000
On the day of the wedding, the bride wore a long white dress and had flowers in her hair.

02:58.000 --> 03:13.000
A pronuba, a married woman friend, often the mother of the bride went with her and stood next to her at the ceremony.

03:14.000 --> 03:26.000
Friends and family came to the wedding and the family needed ten Roman men as witnesses.

03:27.000 --> 03:36.000
After the ceremony, there was a party at the new home of the bride and groom.

03:37.000 --> 03:53.000
And people gave them presents. Later, in western countries, a wedding was a day for the families of the bride and groom.

03:54.000 --> 04:10.000
Sometimes, the father of the bride looked for the best groom for his daughter or the bride's family got help from a matchmaker.

04:11.000 --> 04:19.000
This person met different young men and found the right groom for the bride.

04:20.000 --> 04:34.000
After that, the two families arranged the wedding together and the wedding happened at the bride's house, not at a church.

04:35.000 --> 04:41.000
Here, the bride and the groom got married in front of everybody.

04:42.000 --> 04:52.000
In the 1500s, the wedding moved to the church and there was a ceremony.

04:53.000 --> 05:07.000
Today, in western countries, like the USA, Canada, the UK, Australia and many European countries,

05:08.000 --> 05:26.000
weddings often have a lot of the same things. For example, the bride wears a white and often expensive dress and carries beautiful flowers.

05:27.000 --> 05:41.000
She usually has helpers with her too, friends or perhaps younger girls and sometimes boys from the family.

05:42.000 --> 05:52.000
In this book, we are going to call a wedding like this, a western wedding.

05:53.000 --> 06:04.000
Weddings change over time and different countries and churches all have their own traditions.

06:05.000 --> 06:18.000
Weddings often have things like music or dance from long ago, but they have new things from today too.

06:19.000 --> 06:26.000
People sometimes put together different parts of other wedding traditions.

06:28.000 --> 06:46.000
A Japanese bride wears an American dress or a Brazilian bride has a French wedding cake and as you can see in the next chapters,

06:47.000 --> 06:58.000
people in countries a long way from each other often do the same things for the same reason.

07:04.000 --> 07:09.000
Chapter 2 Before the Wedding

07:16.000 --> 07:30.000
A woman finds a man. A man finds a woman. Perhaps they meet at work, at a party or through friends.

07:31.000 --> 07:38.000
Perhaps a matchmaker helps them or their families arrange the wedding.

07:39.000 --> 07:54.000
When a man asks a woman to marry him, he proposes, of course, the woman can ask the man to marry her.

07:55.000 --> 08:04.000
In some countries, leap day, the 29th of February is the day for this.

08:05.000 --> 08:14.000
When the woman or the man says yes, the couple are engaged.

08:15.000 --> 08:21.000
In western countries, this is called an engagement.

08:22.000 --> 08:38.000
In the photo, you can see Prince William of Wales and Catherine Kate Middleton in London on the day of their engagement.

08:39.000 --> 08:55.000
At the same time as the engagement or soon after, the groom often gives the bride a ring called an engagement ring.

08:56.000 --> 09:03.000
Where does the tradition of the engagement ring come from?

09:04.000 --> 09:17.000
Archduke Maximilian of Austria gave a ring with a diamond to Mary of Burgundy in 1477.

09:18.000 --> 09:31.000
This was the first engagement ring with a diamond, some people say, and a diamond ring is popular today.

09:34.000 --> 09:48.000
The Gimmel ring was popular in Germany, England and other countries in the 1500s and 1600s.

09:49.000 --> 09:53.000
There were two parts to this ring.

09:54.000 --> 10:03.000
When they got engaged, the man wore one part and the woman wore the other part.

10:04.000 --> 10:16.000
Then, when they got married, the two rings went together and made one ring, the woman's wedding ring.

10:17.000 --> 10:22.000
You can buy special rings like these today.

10:23.000 --> 10:29.000
Sometimes, the groom has an engagement ring too.

10:30.000 --> 10:38.000
In Germany, the bride and groom give each other gold rings.

10:39.000 --> 10:53.000
Before the wedding, these go on the left hand and then they go on the right hand and are wedding rings.

10:54.000 --> 11:07.000
In Brazil, the groom gives the bride a ring for her right hand and at the wedding, it goes on her left hand.

11:08.000 --> 11:19.000
In China, some brides wear a ring with jade. This brings them good luck.

11:20.000 --> 11:25.000
At the time of the engagement, there are often presents.

11:26.000 --> 11:37.000
Sometimes, they are between the bride and groom and sometimes between the two families.

11:38.000 --> 11:55.000
In some countries, the groom's family gives money, called the bride price, to the bride's family because the bride is leaving them.

11:56.000 --> 12:11.000
In Indonesia, a groom from a Chinese family gives clothes, gold and money to the bride and her parents.

12:12.000 --> 12:18.000
They look at the presents and give half of them back.

12:19.000 --> 12:32.000
This says to the groom, this is very good of you, but we cannot take all these presents from you.

12:33.000 --> 12:49.000
In Hawaii, the groom's family once gave doors, windows and all the things for a house and the bride's family made the house.

12:50.000 --> 12:56.000
Engagement presents can be lots of different things.

12:56.000 --> 13:13.000
Chickens, in Zaire, flowers called dravitz in Bulgaria and of course cars, money, houses and gold.

13:14.000 --> 13:32.000
After the engagement and before the wedding, the bride often has a party with her women friends called a hen night or bachelorette party.

13:32.000 --> 13:41.000
It is their last time together before the bride leaves them to be a married woman.

13:42.000 --> 13:55.000
It is a time to talk, laugh and perhaps dance together and sometimes to make a lot of noise too.

13:55.000 --> 14:08.000
When the groom goes out with his friends like this, it is called a stag night or bachelor party.

14:09.000 --> 14:21.000
In Hawaii and other parts of the USA, some brides make one thousand little birds from paper.

14:22.000 --> 14:30.000
They do this in the time between the engagement and the wedding.

14:31.000 --> 14:43.000
This tradition comes from Japan and it brings good luck and a long happy life to the couple.

14:43.000 --> 14:59.000
The little birds often white, red or gold are sometimes made into a big picture for the couple's new home.

15:00.000 --> 15:16.000
In the years to come, they can look back at the picture and remember their wedding.

15:16.000 --> 15:34.000
What color does a bride wear at her wedding?

15:34.000 --> 15:45.000
White, of course, but also other colors like red, gold or black.

15:45.000 --> 15:57.000
Most brides at western weddings wear a white dress, but it was not always like this.

15:57.000 --> 16:08.000
Two hundred years ago, rich British brides wore expensive new dresses for the wedding,

16:08.000 --> 16:14.000
and other brides wore their best dress.

16:14.000 --> 16:24.000
Blue was a popular color, but red and black were not.

16:24.000 --> 16:37.000
Everything changed in 1840 at the wedding of the British Queen Victoria to Prince Albert.

16:37.000 --> 16:52.000
Victoria wore a white dress and had white orange blossom, flowers from the orange tree in her hair.

16:52.000 --> 17:05.000
White dresses were soon very popular and a lot of brides wear long white dresses today.

17:05.000 --> 17:12.000
The next most popular color around the world is red.

17:12.000 --> 17:19.000
It is a lucky color for brides in China and India.

17:19.000 --> 17:31.000
In India and Sri Lanka, women sometimes wear beautiful clothes with gold in them too,

17:31.000 --> 17:42.000
and a traditional Spanish bride wears an expensive black wedding dress.

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000
Many brides wear a veil.

17:46.000 --> 17:55.000
This goes over the bride's head and face and is often white.

17:55.000 --> 18:06.000
In some African countries, the bride has a veil of hair over her face.

18:06.000 --> 18:16.000
Brides in India and China often wear a red veil.

18:16.000 --> 18:31.000
In a western wedding, after the bride and groom are married, the groom takes the veil off the bride's face.

18:31.000 --> 18:36.000
What color clothes does the groom wear?

18:36.000 --> 18:47.000
Usually, the answer is a black or dark suit, but not always.

18:47.000 --> 18:56.000
In Hawaii, the groom wears a long white shirt and trousers.

18:56.000 --> 19:08.000
At a traditional Korean wedding, the groom wears red or blue with a tall black hat.

19:08.000 --> 19:20.000
In Spain, the bride traditionally embroidered a beautiful shirt and gave it to the groom.

19:20.000 --> 19:26.000
He wore this new shirt at his wedding.

19:26.000 --> 19:38.000
The Roman bride had her pro-nuba to help her, and today's bride has helpers too.

19:38.000 --> 19:43.000
These are the bridesmaids.

19:43.000 --> 19:53.000
Usually, they are friends of the bride or sisters of the bride or groom.

19:53.000 --> 20:09.000
A married bridesmaid is called a matron of honor, and a very young bridesmaid is called a flower girl.

20:09.000 --> 20:16.000
Young boy helpers are called page boys.

20:16.000 --> 20:25.000
The bridesmaids stay with the bride before and during the wedding.

20:25.000 --> 20:34.000
They help her to put on her clothes and to remember everything.

20:34.000 --> 20:45.000
In earlier times, the bridesmaids and the bride wore the same dresses and veils.

20:45.000 --> 21:00.000
When evil spirits came near the wedding, they could not find the bride because the dresses were all the same.

21:00.000 --> 21:11.000
The groom's helpers are called groom's men, and they help him before and at the wedding.

21:11.000 --> 21:18.000
The most important groom's men is the best man.

21:18.000 --> 21:26.000
Usually, the groom's brother or his best friend.

21:26.000 --> 21:36.000
The best man stays with the groom, carries the rings, and is a witness.

21:36.000 --> 21:46.000
In some countries, the best man is an older man, often a married man.

21:46.000 --> 22:02.000
He helps the bride and groom in their new life too, not just on the day of the wedding.

22:02.000 --> 22:14.000
Chapter 4 Traditional Ceremonies

22:14.000 --> 22:24.000
It is the day of the wedding. Family and friends come together for the ceremony.

22:24.000 --> 22:35.000
There are lots of different ceremonies, of course, but some things happen all over the world.

22:35.000 --> 22:51.000
In a traditional western wedding, the groom, the families and all the other guests come to the church first and wait there for the bride.

22:51.000 --> 23:06.000
The groom doesn't usually see the bride on the morning of the wedding or the night before because it is bad luck.

23:06.000 --> 23:18.000
The bride and her bridesmaids arrive at the church together, often in a big expensive car.

23:18.000 --> 23:31.000
Then, some music begins to play and the bride walks slowly into the church with her father.

23:31.000 --> 23:49.000
In the ceremony, the father gives the bride to the groom and the bride leaves her family and makes a new family with the groom.

23:49.000 --> 24:01.000
The wedding officiant asks the man, Do you take this woman to be your wife?

24:01.000 --> 24:06.000
He answers, I do.

24:06.000 --> 24:17.000
The officiant then asks the woman, Do you take this man to be your husband?

24:17.000 --> 24:23.000
And she answers, I do.

24:23.000 --> 24:32.000
In many ceremonies around the world, the couple drink from the same cup.

24:32.000 --> 24:41.000
In China, the bride and groom drink wine from special cups.

24:41.000 --> 24:50.000
Then, they give the cups to each other and drink again.

24:50.000 --> 25:00.000
In Bulgaria and Russia, the couple drink three times from the same glass.

25:00.000 --> 25:08.000
And in France, they have wine from a very beautiful cup.

25:08.000 --> 25:12.000
A cup de mariage.

25:12.000 --> 25:21.000
This special cup stays in the family for many years.

25:21.000 --> 25:30.000
In Japan, the bride and groom have a drink called sake.

25:30.000 --> 25:36.000
The groom drinks first, then the bride.

25:36.000 --> 25:43.000
And then, the parents of the couple drink too.

25:43.000 --> 25:58.000
Because the bride and groom are beginning a new life together, in many countries, someone ties the couple together.

25:58.000 --> 26:08.000
In a Hindu ceremony, a white thread goes around the couple five times.

26:08.000 --> 26:20.000
In Cambodia, every guest carefully ties a thread around the couple's hands.

26:20.000 --> 26:31.000
And in Thailand, two white threads go between the heads of the bride and groom.

26:31.000 --> 26:45.000
The Hopi people of Arizona, in the USA, cut some hair from the bride and some from the groom.

26:45.000 --> 26:54.000
They then tie the hair together and the couple are married.

26:54.000 --> 27:03.000
In many countries, rings are a very important part of the ceremony.

27:03.000 --> 27:09.000
Sometimes, only the bride gets a ring.

27:09.000 --> 27:17.000
And sometimes the bride and the groom have a wedding ring.

27:17.000 --> 27:23.000
But, of course, rings aren't a new thing.

27:23.000 --> 27:32.000
Thousands of years ago, Egyptian grooms gave a ring to their brides.

27:32.000 --> 27:38.000
And the Romans had wedding rings too.

27:38.000 --> 27:47.000
In some traditional ceremonies, the man or the woman breaks something.

27:47.000 --> 27:54.000
At a Jewish wedding, the groom breaks a glass with his foot.

27:54.000 --> 27:57.000
This brings good luck.

27:57.000 --> 28:05.000
In Bulgaria, the bride quickly throws a plate to the ground.

28:05.000 --> 28:13.000
When the plate breaks, it gives the couple good luck too.

28:13.000 --> 28:23.000
In many countries, the bride and groom write their names in a special book.

28:23.000 --> 28:29.000
And the witnesses write their names too.

28:29.000 --> 28:42.000
In a Muslim wedding, the bride and groom put their names on a special paper called the Nicar Namah.

28:43.000 --> 28:53.000
In a Western wedding, the couple write their names in the special book near the end of the ceremony.

28:53.000 --> 29:08.000
Then music plays, and the newly married husband and wife leave the ceremony together with their friends and families.

29:13.000 --> 29:25.000
Chapter 5 The Reception

29:25.000 --> 29:32.000
After the ceremony, people love a good party.

29:32.000 --> 29:37.000
This is often called a reception.

29:37.000 --> 29:45.000
In Mexico and Italy, it sometimes goes on all night.

29:45.000 --> 29:52.000
And in Russia, it can go on for two days.

29:52.000 --> 30:03.000
A traditional wedding in Morocco goes on for a lot longer, perhaps a week.

30:03.000 --> 30:11.000
Special food is usually an important part of the reception.

30:11.000 --> 30:23.000
In China and Japan, red food is popular because red is a lucky colour.

30:23.000 --> 30:32.000
But the most important food in many countries is a wedding cake.

30:32.000 --> 30:44.000
A Western wedding cake is usually white, with flowers and a little bride and groom on it.

30:44.000 --> 30:53.000
Sometimes the couple put one part of the cake in a box for later.

30:53.000 --> 31:03.000
They eat it a year after their wedding, or when they have a baby.

31:03.000 --> 31:09.000
In France, couples have a cock and bush.

31:09.000 --> 31:20.000
This is made from a lot of little cakes, and it can be one metre high.

31:20.000 --> 31:27.000
In other countries, there is special wedding bread.

31:27.000 --> 31:34.000
In the Ukraine, it is called agorovai.

31:34.000 --> 31:41.000
Seven women make this bread in the home of the bride.

31:41.000 --> 31:49.000
It has two little birds on it, one for the bride and one for the groom.

31:49.000 --> 31:57.000
And the sun, flowers and animals.

31:57.000 --> 32:08.000
People often take photographs of the bride and the groom when they cut the beautiful cake or bread.

32:08.000 --> 32:15.000
It is an important part of the wedding.

32:15.000 --> 32:23.000
At some time in the wedding reception, somebody makes a speech.

32:23.000 --> 32:29.000
They stand up and talk to everyone.

32:29.000 --> 32:38.000
In a Western wedding, the best man and the groom usually speak.

32:38.000 --> 32:43.000
But sometimes the bride speaks too.

32:43.000 --> 32:54.000
They talk about the bride and groom and say thank you to the couple's family and friends.

32:54.000 --> 33:05.000
At the end, they ask for good luck for the bride and groom in their new life.

33:05.000 --> 33:12.000
At a Japanese wedding, some guests make speeches too.

33:12.000 --> 33:21.000
They speak about the happy couple and everyone laughs a lot.

33:21.000 --> 33:32.000
After the speeches at a Russian wedding, the guests all throw their glasses on the ground.

33:32.000 --> 33:39.000
This brings good luck to the new husband and wife.

33:39.000 --> 33:47.000
At the reception, there is usually a lot of music and dancing.

33:47.000 --> 33:59.000
Often the bride and groom have the first dance and then the other guests begin to dance too.

33:59.000 --> 34:07.000
Sometimes there are very famous dances with traditional music.

34:07.000 --> 34:17.000
In Greece and Bulgaria, people dance in a big circle at weddings.

34:17.000 --> 34:24.000
This is very popular at Jewish receptions too.

34:24.000 --> 34:32.000
In part of this dance, the bride and groom sit on chairs

34:32.000 --> 34:38.000
and the other guests carry them around the room.

34:38.000 --> 34:53.000
Often, before the bride leaves the reception, she throws her wonderful flowers to all the other young women at the party.

34:53.000 --> 35:11.000
When one woman gets the bouquet in her hands, she is going to be the next bride, people say.

35:11.000 --> 35:22.000
Chapter 6 Money

35:22.000 --> 35:27.000
Weddings can cost a lot of money.

35:27.000 --> 35:39.000
A traditional wedding in the UK costs between £15,000 and £25,000.

35:39.000 --> 35:51.000
The most expensive thing is usually the reception, about 21% of the cost.

35:51.000 --> 36:03.000
And next is the honeymoon, the bride and groom's holiday at 18%.

36:03.000 --> 36:15.000
The bride's dress, shoes, hair and other things cost about 8%.

36:15.000 --> 36:18.000
Who pays for the wedding?

36:18.000 --> 36:23.000
Usually the bride's parents do this.

36:23.000 --> 36:31.000
But sometimes the couple pay for some or all of the wedding.

36:31.000 --> 36:40.000
In Italy, the bride carries a small bag and guests put money into it.

36:40.000 --> 36:45.000
This money helps to pay for the wedding.

36:45.000 --> 36:59.000
In Poland, young men put money on the bride's dress at the reception and then she dances with them.

36:59.000 --> 37:06.000
People put money on the couple in Greece and Turkey too.

37:06.000 --> 37:16.000
The money pays for part of the honeymoon or for nice things in their new life together.

37:16.000 --> 37:26.000
A tradition in Hungary and Portugal is to leave money in the bride's shoe.

37:26.000 --> 37:38.000
Someone carries the shoe around to all the guests and they put money in it for the couple.

37:38.000 --> 37:45.000
In some countries, the groom gives money as a present.

37:45.000 --> 37:56.000
In China, the groom gives money in red envelopes to the bride's friends on the day of the wedding

37:56.000 --> 38:03.000
because he is taking her away from her friends.

38:03.000 --> 38:11.000
Later, the bride gives tea to everyone in the groom's family.

38:11.000 --> 38:19.000
And they give her red envelopes with money in them.

38:19.000 --> 38:32.000
In Spain, Mexico, and some other countries, the groom gives the bride 13 gold coins

38:32.000 --> 38:38.000
called aras at the end of the wedding ceremony.

38:38.000 --> 38:46.000
The groom often brings the coins in an expensive aras box.

38:46.000 --> 38:52.000
He gives them to the bride one at a time.

38:52.000 --> 39:00.000
Now, all of his things are her things too.

39:00.000 --> 39:10.000
As we saw earlier, in many countries, the groom gives money to the bride's family

39:10.000 --> 39:14.000
when the couple get engaged.

39:14.000 --> 39:24.000
People can give this money the bride price at the time of the wedding too.

39:24.000 --> 39:29.000
But it is not only money.

39:29.000 --> 39:38.000
The bride price can be gold, animals, clothes and food.

39:38.000 --> 39:47.000
This happens today in countries like Pakistan and Uganda.

39:47.000 --> 39:58.000
At a Muslim wedding, the groom must pay some money called Meher to the bride.

39:58.000 --> 40:06.000
You can pay a little money for a wedding or a lot of money.

40:06.000 --> 40:12.000
But you can pay millions and millions of dollars too.

40:12.000 --> 40:28.000
The two sons of the rich Indian man, Subrata Roy, got married in 2004 in Lucknow in the north of India.

40:28.000 --> 40:34.000
More than 10,000 guests came to the wedding.

40:34.000 --> 40:50.000
Mr Roy brought 100 people from the UK to play music at the wedding and 1,800 people made the food.

40:50.000 --> 40:59.000
There was Indian, Chinese, Italian and Lebanese food.

40:59.000 --> 41:10.000
And it was a happy day for 101 couples without very much money in Lucknow.

41:10.000 --> 41:24.000
Mr Roy paid for a big wedding for them and gave them wedding presents of beds, TV's and gold rings.

41:24.000 --> 41:34.000
He gave food to 140,000 people in different parts of India too.

41:34.000 --> 41:40.000
What did it all cost? Nobody knows.

41:40.000 --> 41:55.000
But the answer is between 30 million and 70 million dollars, people say.

41:55.000 --> 42:05.000
Chapter 7. Two weddings.

42:05.000 --> 42:13.000
This chapter is about two weddings in two different countries.

42:13.000 --> 42:18.000
The first wedding was in England.

42:18.000 --> 42:28.000
Graham and Kendra got married in London in summer 2009.

42:28.000 --> 42:37.000
They are English but they met in Bosnia in 2005.

42:37.000 --> 42:46.000
I proposed to Kendra there in February 2009.

42:46.000 --> 42:52.000
On a mountain in the snow said Graham.

42:52.000 --> 43:03.000
I gave her a ring and other presents and we went out to dinner that evening.

43:03.000 --> 43:09.000
We then began to get ready for the wedding said Kendra.

43:09.000 --> 43:15.000
We wanted to get married at my church.

43:15.000 --> 43:26.000
This was all souls church, a beautiful old building on Regent Street in London.

43:26.000 --> 43:34.000
The day of the wedding was the 18th of July in the summer.

43:34.000 --> 43:47.000
It was a good time for the wedding because a lot of people have a holiday at that time of year.

43:47.000 --> 43:57.000
Two weeks before the wedding I had a wonderful hen day with my friends loved Kendra.

43:57.000 --> 44:01.000
I remember it very well.

44:01.000 --> 44:09.000
We all met in Regent's Park in London and stayed there for a day.

44:09.000 --> 44:18.000
Graham and his friends went to Bath in the west of England for his stag night.

44:18.000 --> 44:24.000
Their nice dinner and some some minks together.

44:24.000 --> 44:28.000
Then the day the wedding arrived.

44:28.000 --> 44:32.000
It was a war Saturday in July.

44:32.000 --> 44:35.000
I remember Graham.

44:35.000 --> 44:48.000
Guests came from the UK and from Bosnia, Bulgaria where the USA and Afghanistan too.

44:48.000 --> 44:52.000
Kendra had three bridesmaids.

44:52.000 --> 45:00.000
Her sister, my sister and a friend from Bosnia.

45:00.000 --> 45:09.000
My best man was my friend Harris and we had had groomsmen.

45:09.000 --> 45:17.000
The colors for our wedding were dark blue and gold said Kendra.

45:17.000 --> 45:29.000
So the bridesmaids wore dark up the dresses and the groomsmen all had dark blue shirts.

